				 Hostile witnesses worry widow
 															- Slain doctors wife seeks help from physicians in her fight for justice A STAFF REPORTER				 	 Kanika Pal, widow of slain doctor Sushil Pal																								The spate of witnesses turning hostile has prompted the widow of gynaecologist Sushil Pal to seek help from doctors across the state in her fight against her husbands murderers.																								Around 80 per cent of the 106 witnesses produced by the CID have turned hostile. The sleuths suspect that they were retracting their statements under pressure from the CPM, as most of the accused were close to party leaders.																								The way one witness after another is turning hostile, I fear all the accused will be acquitted. I am desperately seeking help from doctors  my husband was one of them  in my quest for justice, said Kanika Pal, who lives in Gariahat.																								The witnesses statements before the judge of the Howrah district court is not matching what the CID has mentioned in the chargesheet. Who are speaking the truth  the sleuths or the witnesses? wondered Kanika.																								She has written to the Indian Medical Association, Association of Health Service Doctors and the Students Association of Medical College and Hospital.																								Sanjay Banerjee, of the state branch of the Indian Medical Association, said: We have written to the state home secretary on November 13, requesting him to look into the matter. We will write to the chief minister if no action is taken by November 30.																								Gautam Mukhopadhyay, of the Association of Health Service Doctors (West Bengal), said: The matter will be brought to the notice of the state government.																								The mud-caked body of Pal, who worked at Serampore Walsh Hospital, was found in a canal in Sankrail, Howrah, on July 3, 2004. A probe revealed that he was murdered at a nursing home in Bally after he refused to conduct an abortion on another gynaecologist. Thirteen persons  including the owner of the nursing home, Biswajyoti Basu, and the woman doctor, Piyali Das Mandal were arrested. Piyali and six others were granted bail.
